text.tspan: A Bayesian model of memory in a multi-context environment

flowRoot.flowPara: What is a context, and how do you know?
This is a clustering problem:
what are cluster labels z1:i for data points x1:i
Ideal observer/Bayesian approach:
calculate p(z1:i | x1:i) p(x1:i | z1:i) p(z1:i)
likelihood p(x1:i | z1:i): prefer compact clusters
prior p(z1:i): prefer fewer/larger clusters
("sticky" Chinese Restaurant Process)
200 immediate masked spatial recall trials
Studied locations occurred in latent clusters

text.tspan: Multiple clusters very close to the center

flowRoot.flowPara: Subjects recall deviation direction is biased towards latent cluster centers (cosine similarity 0.09, p < 0.001 using uniform response null)
There are too many possible clusterings z1:i to count, but most have very low probability
We approximate the posterior p(z | x) with a weighted collection of particles, each a particular value of z (hypothesis about the clusters of the data seen so far)
Each particle is updated in parallel as new data comes in, sampling a cluster label for the new point given its hypothesis about the clusters so far
: Eagerness to create new clusters (concentration)
: Stickiness (probability to stay in same cluster)
: Memory uncertainty
Model (mostly) recovers latent clusters, except when model thinks an old cluster is revisited

g.text: Adjusted Rand Index with true clusters

text.tspan: Probability each pair agrees with true blocks

flowRoot.flowPara: Model recall deviation aligns with behavior:
better than baselines:
random response in circle,
always bias towards center or mean radius (Huttenlocher 1991).
comparable with (and sometimes better than) known clusters.
best for low concentration , high stickiness
Subjects also occasionally predicted the location that dots would appear in 1, 5, or 10 trials
For longer predictions: tend to predict farther from last studied location, and return to center cluster
Model qualitatively captures tendency to predict a return to center at longer delays
Model quantitatively captures predictions farther from last studied location at longer delays
Model further captures trial-by-trial variation within delay levels
